items.title: Grunge 101
items.description: Grunge was born from an intense dislike of the ever-bombastic mainstream sheen of hair metal. The genre germinated in the late ‘80s in the Pacific Northwest, merging hardcore punk, heavy metal and noise rock to raucous results. It entered the mainstream on the backs of Nirvana and the Sub Pop label in the ‘90s, and went on to influence decades of indie-rock bands to come. Check out a selection of some of the most memorable and famous grunge artists and songs with this playlist. (Cover: Pearl Jam and Nirvana, Photo: Rovi)

items.title: Smashing Pumpkins Essentials
items.description: Formed by frontman Billy Corgan and guitarist James Iha, Smashing Pumpkins emerged from Chicago in the late ‘80s, just in time to surf the wave of alternative and grunge acts that defined the time. Although they are often mentioned in the same breath as contemporaries peers, Nirvana, Alice In Chains, and Pearl Jam, the Pumpkins were a band that rejected punk and and mainstream ambitious alike, in favor of pursuing their own unique sound. Their influence has been integral for subsequent alternative acts of the 2000s, vocally by My Chemical Romance and Nelly Furtado. Smashing Pumpkins’ debut, Gish (1991), was produced by Butch Vig (who also helmed Nirvana's Nevermind) and became a success on the alternative charts. Their real breakthrough came with Siamese Dream (1993), with songs like "Disarm," "Today" and "Cherub Rock". With Mellon Collie And The Infinite Sadness (1995), the Pumpkins flew straight to the top of the Billboard charts, cementing the band's position as one of the ‘90s great staples. They took a more electric direction with Adore (1998), while the MACHINA/The Machines of God (2000) returned them to their rock roots. The original group dissolved in 2000, but after some years of silence, Corgan brought Smashing Pumpkins back to life with Zeitgeist (2007) and has remained prolific with the band ever since. (Photo: Press)

items.title: Pixies Essentials
items.description: Pixies started in Boston in 1986, and immediately stood out on the alternative rock charts. Surfer Rosa (1988) and Doolittle (1989) are among the most influential albums in the last 25 years, and had a direct influence of indie/alternative rock explosion of the ‘90s and beyond. Bands like Nirvana, Weezer, Pavement and Modest Mouse are all children of the Pixies' distinctive style. Their roots can be traced to Iggy Pop and Captain Beefheart, post-punk (Wire, Pere Ubu), noise rock (Sonic Youth, Hüsker Dü) and power pop (Big Star, Cheap Trick). With an endless punk energy, Pixies mixed those influences into a deliciously strong cocktail all their own, which rarely fell into the mainstream. Marked by only limited success, the band released only four albums during their initial career. After a long breakup, they first reunited briefly in 2003. Following the success of the Doolittle 20th anniversary tour in 2010, and having found a new generation of fans, the band reunited more permanently and, despite the departure of bassist Kim Deal, have begun releasing new material again. (Photo: Rovi)

items.title: Foo Fighters Essentials
items.description: Melding heavy rock guitars, driving punk sensibilities and pretty melodies, Foo Fighters rose to become one of the biggest acts to emerge out of the alt-rock boom of the 1990s. Led by singer Dave Grohl, the former powerhouse drummer for Nirvana, Foo Fighters initially debuted as a solo project in 1995. However, as their lineup expanded, they steadily racked up success after success, filling stadiums around the world while staying near the top of the charts with hits like "My Hero" and "Everlong" off 1997's 'The Colour and the Shape.' Once the band's lineup coalesced around the time of its third album, 1999's 'There Is Nothing Left to Lose,' Foo Fighters' sound also gelled into a recognizable signature built upon the heavy yet melodic, loud-quiet-loud template of Pixies and Nirvana; a modern-rock sound anchored by Grohl's love of classic guitar rock. It was commercial without pandering and creatively restless without being alienating, a sound with wide appeal delivered by a band that was happy to tour and record the way bands did back in the '70s. Accolades followed, including winning Grammy Awards for 1999's 'There Is Nothing Left to Lose,' 2002's 'One by One' and 2007's 'Echoes, Silence, Patience & Grace,' all of which also charted in the Top Three of the Billboard 200. When 'Wasting Light' became their first No. 1 album in America upon its release in the spring of 2011, it was confirmation that Foo Fighters were survivors who had earned a large, devoted audience primarily through hard work. Along with their dedication to touring and their continued chart dominance, Foo Fighters have experimented with their sound, drawing inspiration from the rock traditions of iconic cities across America on 2014's 'Sonic Highways,' delving into prog rock on 2017's 'Concrete and Gold,' and embracing danceable, feel-good anthems on 2021's 'Medicine at Midnight.' Drummer Taylor Hawkins died tragically on March 25, 2022, just 50 years old. (Photo and bio: Rovi)

items.title: Pearl Jam Essentials
items.description: Pearl Jam has its roots in the Seattle grunge scene - including former members of Green River and Mother Love Bone - but they quickly grew out of the genre's bosom to establish themselves on their own terms and become one of the biggest bands of the last 20 years. Their immortal debut, Ten (1991), was marked by somber themes dressed in an ambitious expression. Ten took nearly a year to break through after its initial release, but when it finally made it to the charts the record stayed there for over two years and remains one of the highest-selling rock albums of all time. Pearl Jam got their success in line with grunge wave that swept over the world in the early ‘90s (Nirvana, Alice In Chains, Soundgarden), but was also criticized as a poser-band who tried to surf on that scene’s popularity. However, time would prove that they were among the most alternative and independent-minded bands out there, outlasting just about every one of their contemporaries. With sequels Vs. (1993) and Vitalogy (1994) they toned down the commercial appeal, yet both releases still managed to become some of the highest-selling albums of the decade. Around the same time the band began their long struggle against high ticket prices and scalping, and remain vocal critics for the exploitation of their fans. Pearl Jam remains an influential and active band that, despite their massive success, have never compromised their artistic integrity. (Photo: Danny Clinch, press)

items.title: 1989! Songs of the Year
items.description: 1989 was the year the Berlin Wall started to crack open, the beginning of the Velvet Revolution in Eastern Europe and the not so peaceful Tiananmen Square protests in China. It was also a pretty good year in music, with landmark albums from major artists like Madonna, Janet Jackson and Tom Petty. This was the golden age of hip-hop, and it was the final days of mainstream hardrock before the grunge craze swept the world – introducing the world to debut full-length albums from Nirvana, Mudhoney, Tad and Soundgarden. Albums from The Pixies, The Stone Roses and Depeche Mode helped crossing the alternative into the mainstream. Listen to the sound of 1989 with this playlist, including time typical tunes, the biggest hits and some forgotten gems. [This list of yearly songs follows the rule of earliest release date.] (Cover: Madonna - Like a Prayer, Sire/Warner)

items.title: Perfect Guitar Riffs
items.description: TIDAL is exploring the concept of "perfection" in music. Each playlist in the "Perfect" series is limited to 20 tracks, and is the result of a painful (and, oftentimes, loud) debate among our team of expert curators. One thing we can all agree on is that these songs – across different genres, eras and reputation – represent the ultimate peak for a related occasion or theme. So please dig in or disagree. Or both. These are our 20 Perfect Guitar Riffs. (Photo: Unsplash)
